00:34:08.550 --> 00:34:10.469
another even more
magnificent sequence

00:34:10.469 --> 00:34:14.310
to show you to finish
out this attempt

00:34:14.310 --> 00:34:17.090
to give you at least a quick
flavor of the varieties

00:34:17.090 --> 00:34:19.389
of experience available
in the musical

00:34:19.389 --> 00:34:22.690
before we look at a fully
integrated musical this evening

00:34:22.690 --> 00:34:23.889
with Singin' in the Rain.

00:34:23.889 --> 00:34:27.230
Let me say very quickly
then, to jump to the bottom,

00:34:27.230 --> 00:34:31.550
the final aspect of this is what
Arthur Freed and his cohorts

00:34:31.550 --> 00:34:35.960
articulated as the idea of a
musical that would integrate

00:34:35.960 --> 00:34:40.570
sufficiently music and dance
with character and story

00:34:40.570 --> 00:34:42.070
in a way that would be coherent.

00:34:42.070 --> 00:34:45.530
And the musicals made under
Arthur Freed's direction, often

00:34:45.530 --> 00:34:48.409
called the "Freed
Unit" at MGM, tried

00:34:48.409 --> 00:34:50.550
to satisfy this criterion.

00:34:50.550 --> 00:34:52.929
They were, in many
ways, more coherent

00:34:52.929 --> 00:34:55.630
in terms of the relation
between the singing

00:34:55.630 --> 00:34:58.490
and the dancing and the story
than these earlier forms

00:34:58.490 --> 00:35:00.940
were, although they were
often less imaginatively

00:35:00.940 --> 00:35:04.660
expressive in some cases,
although this is not true,

00:35:04.660 --> 00:35:08.180
I think, of Singin' in the Rain.

00:35:08.180 --> 00:35:11.330
But there is another stage to
mention in this development

00:35:11.330 --> 00:35:13.700
or evolution, and it's
one of the most important

00:35:13.700 --> 00:35:15.580
in the history of the
Hollywood musical.

00:35:15.580 --> 00:35:17.880
And it has to do with the
partnership between Fred

00:35:17.880 --> 00:35:21.950
Astaire and Ginger Rogers,
mostly at the RKO studios.

00:35:21.950 --> 00:35:27.800
They made nine films together
between 1933 in 1939 at RKO.

00:35:27.800 --> 00:35:29.600
And they introduced
another element

00:35:29.600 --> 00:35:33.490
into the musical film
that is then, I think,

00:35:33.490 --> 00:35:38.720
incorporated in a certain degree
in the so-called integrated

00:35:38.720 --> 00:35:39.910
musical of MGM.

00:35:39.910 --> 00:35:42.010
So my last example
this afternoon

00:35:42.010 --> 00:35:45.650
comes from the
great Astaire-Rogers

00:35:45.650 --> 00:35:47.280
musical, Top Hat.

00:35:47.280 --> 00:35:49.420
And let me set
the stage for you.

00:35:49.420 --> 00:35:52.590
Get ready to show it because
we're running out of time.

00:35:52.590 --> 00:35:55.460
The situation is this--
and it dramatizes even more

00:35:55.460 --> 00:35:59.120
fully the idea that there are
potentially sexual tensions,

00:35:59.120 --> 00:36:03.940
sexual themes embedded in the
experience of watching a song

00:36:03.940 --> 00:36:06.590
and dance musical.

00:36:06.590 --> 00:36:09.580
What the Astaire-Rogers
musicals brought

00:36:09.580 --> 00:36:11.880
to the table that had
not been there before

00:36:11.880 --> 00:36:15.960
was, in some sense, a kind
of psychological element.

00:36:15.960 --> 00:36:18.900
Even though in the
Astaire-Rogers films,

00:36:18.900 --> 00:36:20.390
the singing and
dancing was still

00:36:20.390 --> 00:36:23.270
in some sense much more central
to the film than the rest

00:36:23.270 --> 00:36:25.930
of the story, and the stories
were often thin, what they did

00:36:25.930 --> 00:36:28.484
introduce was an individuation.

00:36:28.484 --> 00:36:29.900
In the Busby
Berkeley numbers, you

00:36:29.900 --> 00:36:32.480
can see the women are--
all the characters in fact

00:36:32.480 --> 00:36:36.500
are-- hard to differentiate
from the backdrop

00:36:36.500 --> 00:36:37.390
or from the curtains.

00:36:37.390 --> 00:36:40.050
They are objectified
in a certain way.

00:36:40.050 --> 00:36:41.890
Especially when he
gets going, they

00:36:41.890 --> 00:36:44.070
become parts of an
abstract pattern.

00:36:44.070 --> 00:36:48.270
In the Astaire-Rogers films,
Astaire and Roger's characters

00:36:48.270 --> 00:36:50.330
are deeply, sharply
individuated,

00:36:50.330 --> 00:36:52.560
and certain kinds of
psychological themes

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:53.699
begin to enter in.

00:36:53.699 --> 00:36:55.240
In this clip you're
going to see now,

00:36:55.240 --> 00:36:58.640
a fairly characteristic one and
probably the single most famous

00:36:58.640 --> 00:37:01.770
dance number in the
history of the studio era,

00:37:01.770 --> 00:37:05.660
a dance number based on
the song "Cheek to Cheek,"

00:37:05.660 --> 00:37:11.370
danced by Astaire and
Rogers-- in this sequence,

00:37:11.370 --> 00:37:14.000
we are in a setting that's
worth mentioning to you.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:15.940
We're on board a cruise ship.

00:37:15.940 --> 00:37:17.660
Wealthy Americans are there.

00:37:17.660 --> 00:37:20.700
It's wealthy
people, aristocrats.

00:37:20.700 --> 00:37:26.490
The Astaire and Rogers
characters have met earlier,

00:37:26.490 --> 00:37:28.760
and they haven't
really hit it off.

00:37:28.760 --> 00:37:31.580
And the Rogers
character, the woman,

00:37:31.580 --> 00:37:37.800
thinks that Fred Astaire is an
immoral man, that he commits

00:37:37.800 --> 00:37:39.390
infidelities against his wife.

00:37:39.390 --> 00:37:41.840
And she's under the
mistaken impression

00:37:41.840 --> 00:37:44.800
that the woman he's
with is his wife.

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:46.840
So what happens in the
sequence, essentially,

00:37:46.840 --> 00:37:50.750
is that in front of what
she believes to be his wife,

00:37:50.750 --> 00:37:53.660
he asks her to dance-- he
asks Rogers to dance with her,

00:37:53.660 --> 00:37:57.200
and then, to her surprise,
Astaire's apparent wife

00:37:57.200 --> 00:37:58.080
says, oh, go ahead.

00:37:58.080 --> 00:37:59.630
I'd love to see
you two together.

00:37:59.630 --> 00:38:04.280
And she says, well, I'm--
and so when the dance begins,

00:38:04.280 --> 00:38:05.800
she's sort of resistant.

00:38:05.800 --> 00:38:07.610
She thinking, ah,
this is disgus--

00:38:07.610 --> 00:38:09.896
and she goes along
with it, but she

00:38:09.896 --> 00:38:11.520
feels there's something
wrong about it.

00:38:11.520 --> 00:38:13.080
And then as the
dance goes on, you

00:38:13.080 --> 00:38:15.850
can see her resistance
begin to break down.

00:38:15.850 --> 00:38:19.010
And you can see the dance
becoming more and more mutual.

00:38:19.010 --> 00:38:22.710
And you can see her enthusiasm
for the dance increase.

00:38:22.710 --> 00:38:25.720
And think about what
the dance, first

00:38:25.720 --> 00:38:29.230
of all, how profound
and brilliant this dance

00:38:29.230 --> 00:38:33.440
is as an embodiment of
mutuality and collaboration

00:38:33.440 --> 00:38:36.060
because one of the reasons
Rogers was so remarkable

00:38:36.060 --> 00:38:38.230
was that she was
capable of dancing

00:38:38.230 --> 00:38:42.710
at the same complex, astonishing
level as Fred Astaire himself.

00:38:42.710 --> 00:38:47.000
And it's an image of mutuality
and of collaborative artistry

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:48.270
that's very remarkable.

00:38:48.270 --> 00:38:50.340
But it's also a
metaphor for other kinds

00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:52.990
of mutual interactions
that are physical.

00:38:52.990 --> 00:38:56.040
And I hope you will pay
attention to that subtext

00:38:56.040 --> 00:38:58.750
as you're watching this
remarkable sequence.

00:38:58.750 --> 00:39:04.140
The fact that Rogers begins in
an act-- hostilely, resistant,

00:39:04.140 --> 00:39:07.900
and yields slowly is a key
to the energy we see here.

